---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is yield to maturity (YTM) and how is it calculated?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yield to maturity (YTM) is the total annualized return an investor earns if they hold a bond until it matures, assuming all coupon payments are reinvested at the same rate. YTM accounts for the bond's current market price, face value, coupon rate, and time to maturity. It is calculated using an iterative numerical method (Newton-Raphson) because there is no closed-form algebraic solution. YTM is the single most important metric for comparing bonds because it captures both coupon income and any capital gain or loss from buying at a discount or premium."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is the difference between current yield and yield to maturity?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Current yield is simply the annual coupon payment divided by the bond's current market price — it only measures income return and ignores capital gains or losses. Yield to maturity (YTM) is a more complete measure that factors in the difference between the purchase price and face value at maturity, plus the time value of money. For example, a bond with a 5% coupon bought at $950 (discount) has a current yield of 5.26%, but its YTM would be higher because the investor also gains $50 at maturity. Current yield overstates return for premium bonds and understates it for discount bonds."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is bond duration and why does it matter?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Bond duration measures a bond's sensitivity to interest rate changes, expressed in years. Macaulay duration is the weighted average time until cash flows are received. Modified duration estimates the percentage price change for a 1% change in yield. For example, a bond with modified duration of 7 will lose approximately 7% of its value if yields rise by 1%. Duration matters because it quantifies interest rate risk — longer duration means more price volatility. Investors use duration to match assets with liabilities and to position portfolios for expected rate changes."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What do bond ratings mean and how do they affect yield?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Bond ratings assess the creditworthiness of the issuer — their ability to make interest payments and repay principal. Ratings range from AAA (highest quality, lowest default risk) to D (in default). Investment-grade bonds are rated BBB/Baa or higher; below that are high-yield or 'junk' bonds. Higher-rated bonds offer lower yields because they carry less risk. The yield spread between a corporate bond and a Treasury bond of the same maturity reflects the credit risk premium. A BBB-rated bond might yield 1-2% more than a Treasury, while a BB-rated bond might yield 3-4% more."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"How do interest rates affect bond prices?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Bond prices and interest rates move inversely. When market interest rates rise, existing bonds with lower coupon rates become less attractive, so their prices fall to bring their effective yield in line with new rates. When rates fall, existing bonds with higher coupons become more valuable, pushing prices above face value. The magnitude of this effect depends on the bond's duration — longer-term bonds are more sensitive to rate changes. A 30-year Treasury will lose far more value from a 1% rate hike than a 2-year Treasury. This inverse relationship is the fundamental principle of bond investing."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is convexity and how does it improve on duration?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Convexity measures the curvature in the relationship between bond prices and yields. Duration provides a linear approximation of price sensitivity, but actual bond price changes follow a curve. Convexity captures this non-linearity. For large yield changes, duration alone underestimates price gains when yields fall and overestimates losses when yields rise. Higher convexity is generally favorable because the bond gains more when rates drop than it loses when rates rise (all else equal). Convexity is most important for large rate moves and long-duration bonds where the linear duration approximation breaks down."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is the difference between a premium bond and a discount bond?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"A premium bond trades above its face value (par), which happens when the bond's coupon rate is higher than current market yields. Investors pay extra for the higher income stream. A discount bond trades below par, meaning its coupon rate is lower than prevailing yields. Premium bonds have YTM lower than their coupon rate because the investor loses the premium at maturity. Discount bonds have YTM higher than their coupon rate because the investor gains the discount at maturity. At par, the coupon rate equals the YTM. Understanding this relationship is key to evaluating whether a bond is fairly priced."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"How do I compare two bonds with different maturities and coupon rates?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The best way to compare bonds with different characteristics is to look at yield to maturity (YTM) as the primary metric — it normalizes coupon rates and maturities into a single annualized return figure. Then examine duration to understand interest rate risk differences. A bond with higher YTM but much longer duration carries more rate risk. Also compare credit ratings to ensure you're comparing similar risk levels. The yield spread (difference in YTM) between two bonds should reflect their differences in credit quality, maturity, and liquidity. Use side-by-side analysis with our bond comparison tool above."}}
  ]
};

export const meta = {
  title: "Bond Yield Calculator — YTM, Current Yield & Duration Tool",
  description: "Calculate yield to maturity (YTM), current yield, duration, and convexity for any bond. Compare bonds side by side with price-yield curve visualization.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-21",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title="Bond Yield Calculator: YTM, Current Yield & Duration Analysis"
  description="Calculate yield to maturity (YTM), current yield, bond duration, and convexity. Visual price-yield curve, side-by-side bond comparison, and credit ratings reference table."
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/bond-yield-calculator" schema={schema}
>
  <style is:inline>
.container{max-width:1200px;margin:0 auto;padding:0 20px}
a{color:var(--accent-color);text-decoration:none}
a:hover{text-decoration:underline}

header{padding:40px 0 20px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-color)}
.badge{display:inline-block;background:var(--accent-color);color:#fff;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1.5px;padding:4px 12px;border-radius:3px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:12px}
h1{font-size:clamp(28px,4vw,42px);font-weight:800;line-height:1.15;margin-bottom:8px}
.subtitle{color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:18px;max-width:700px}
.updated-badge{display:inline-block;background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:12px;padding:4px 10px;border-radius:4px;margin-top:8px;font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace}

/* Calculator */
.calc-section{margin:32px 0}
.calc-section h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}
.calc-grid{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:24px}
.calc-inputs{background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;padding:24px}
.calc-results{background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;padding:24px}
.input-group{margin-bottom:16px}
.input-group label{display:block;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.5px;color:var(--text-secondary);margin-bottom:6px}
.input-group input,.input-group select{width:100%;background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);color:var(--text-primary);padding:10px 12px;border-radius:6px;font-size:14px;font-family:'Inter',sans-serif;box-sizing:border-box}
.input-group input:focus,.input-group select:focus{outline:none;border-color:var(--accent-color)}
.input-row{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:12px}
.input-row-3{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:12px}
.input-hint{font-size:11px;color:var(--text-secondary);margin-top:4px}
.calc-btn{width:100%;padding:12px;background:var(--accent-color);color:#fff;border:none;border-radius:6px;font-size:15px;font-weight:600;cursor:pointer;margin-top:8px}
.calc-btn:hover{opacity:.9}

/* Results */
.result-grid{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:12px;margin-bottom:20px}
.result-grid-4{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:12px;margin-bottom:20px}
.result-box{text-align:center;padding:16px 8px;background:rgba(74,143,231,.04);border-radius:8px;border:1px solid var(--border-color)}
.result-box .val{font-size:28px;font-weight:800;font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;color:var(--accent-color)}
.result-box .val.sm{font-size:20px}
.result-box .label{font-size:11px;color:var(--text-secondary);margin-top:4px;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.5px}
.result-box.highlight{border-color:var(--accent-color);background:rgba(74,143,231,.08)}
.result-placeholder{text-align:center;padding:40px 20px;color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px}

/* Price-Yield Chart */
.chart-section{margin:32px 0}
.chart-section h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}
.chart-wrap{background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;padding:24px}
.chart-canvas-wrap{position:relative;width:100%;height:300px}
.chart-canvas-wrap canvas{width:100%;height:100%}

/* Bond Comparison */
.comparison-section{margin:32px 0}
.comparison-section h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}
.comp-container{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:24px}
.comp-bond{background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;padding:20px}
.comp-bond h3{font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px;color:var(--accent-color)}
.comp-results{background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;padding:20px;margin-top:16px}
.comp-table{width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:13px}
.comp-table th{text-align:left;padding:8px 12px;font-size:11px;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.5px;color:var(--text-secondary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-color)}
.comp-table td{padding:8px 12px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-color);font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace}
.comp-table .better{color:#22c55e;font-weight:600}
.comp-table .worse{color:#ef4444}

/* Bond Pricing */
.pricing-section{margin:32px 0}
.pricing-section h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}
.pricing-grid{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:24px}
.price-sensitivity{display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(7,1fr);gap:4px;text-align:center;margin-top:12px}
.price-cell{padding:8px 2px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(255,255,255,.02);border:1px solid var(--border-color)}
.price-cell.current{background:rgba(74,143,231,.1);border:1px solid var(--accent-color)}
.price-cell .pc-yield{color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:10px;font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace}
.price-cell .pc-price{font-weight:700;font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:12px;margin-top:2px}

/* Ratings Table */
.ratings-section{margin:32px 0}
.ratings-section h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}
.table-wrap{overflow-x:auto;border-radius:8px;border:1px solid var(--border-color)}
table{width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:13px}
th{background:#0c1428;color:var(--text-secondary);font-weight:600;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.5px;padding:12px 14px;text-align:left;white-space:nowrap;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-color)}
td{padding:10px 14px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-color)}
tr:hover{background:rgba(74,143,231,.06)}
.num{font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;text-align:right}
.pos{color:#22c55e}
.neg{color:#ef4444}
.rating-badge{display:inline-block;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:700;font-size:12px;font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace}
.rating-ig{background:rgba(34,197,94,.15);color:#22c55e}
.rating-hy{background:rgba(245,158,11,.15);color:#f59e0b}
.rating-d{background:rgba(239,68,68,.15);color:#ef4444}

/* Cash Flow Table */
.cashflow-section{margin:32px 0}
.cashflow-section h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}

/* Findings */
.findings{margin:32px 0}
.findings h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}
.finding-card{background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;padding:20px;margin-bottom:12px}
.finding-card h3{font-size:16px;margin-bottom:6px;color:var(--accent-color)}
.finding-card p{color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px;line-height:1.7}

/* FAQ */
.faq-section{margin:32px 0}
.faq-section h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}
.faq-item{background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;margin-bottom:10px;overflow:hidden}
.faq-q{padding:16px 20px;font-weight:600;cursor:pointer;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center}
.faq-q:hover{color:var(--accent-color)}
.faq-q::after{content:'+';font-size:20px;color:var(--text-secondary);transition:transform .2s}
.faq-item.open .faq-q::after{transform:rotate(45deg);color:var(--accent-color)}
.faq-a{padding:0 20px 16px;color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;display:none}
.faq-item.open .faq-a{display:block}

/* Related */
.related-section{margin:32px 0}
.related-section h2{font-size:22px;margin-bottom:16px}
.related-grid{display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(240px,1fr));gap:12px}
.related-card{background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;padding:16px;text-decoration:none;transition:border-color .2s}
.related-card:hover{border-color:var(--accent-color);text-decoration:none}
.related-card h3{font-size:15px;margin-bottom:4px;color:var(--text-primary)}
.related-card p{font-size:13px;color:var(--text-secondary)}

.methodology{margin:32px 0;background:var(--card-bg);border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;padding:24px}
.methodology h2{font-size:18px;margin-bottom:12px}
.methodology p{color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px;margin-bottom:10px;line-height:1.7}

.disclaimer{margin:20px 0;padding:16px;border:1px solid var(--border-color);border-radius:8px;font-size:12px;color:var(--text-secondary);text-align:center;font-style:italic}

footer{border-top:1px solid var(--border-color);padding:24px 0;text-align:center;color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:13px;margin-top:40px}

@media(max-width:768px){
  .calc-grid,.comp-container,.pricing-grid{grid-template-columns:1fr}
  .result-grid-4{grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr}
  .result-grid{grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr}
  .input-row-3{grid-template-columns:1fr}
  .related-grid{grid-template-columns:1fr}
}
@media(max-width:480px){
  .result-grid{grid-template-columns:1fr}
  .result-grid-4{grid-template-columns:1fr}
  .input-row{grid-template-columns:1fr}
}
  </style>

<div class="container">
    <h1>Bond Yield Calculator: YTM, Current Yield &amp; Duration</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Calculate yield to maturity, current yield, duration, and convexity for any bond. Visualize the price-yield relationship and compare bonds side by side.</p>
    <div class="updated-badge">Last Updated: March 2026</div>

    <div class="calc-section">
      <h2>Calculate Bond Yield</h2>
      <div class="calc-grid">
        <div class="calc-inputs">
          <div class="input-row">
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Face Value ($)</label>
              <input type="number" id="faceValue" value="1000" step="100" min="0">
              <div class="input-hint">Par value at maturity (typically $1,000)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Current Price ($)</label>
              <input type="number" id="currentPrice" placeholder="e.g. 950" step="0.01" min="0">
              <div class="input-hint">Market price you'd pay today</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-row">
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Coupon Rate (%)</label>
              <input type="number" id="couponRate" placeholder="e.g. 5.0" step="0.01" min="0">
              <div class="input-hint">Annual coupon rate as a percentage</div>
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Years to Maturity</label>
              <input type="number" id="yearsToMaturity" placeholder="e.g. 10" step="0.5" min="0.5">
              <div class="input-hint">Time remaining until bond matures</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-group">
            <label>Payment Frequency</label>
            <select id="paymentFreq">
              <option value="2">Semi-Annual (most common)</option>
              <option value="1">Annual</option>
              <option value="4">Quarterly</option>
            </select>
          </div>
          <button class="calc-btn" id="calcBtn">Calculate Bond Yield</button>
        </div>
        <div class="calc-results" id="calcResults">
          <div class="result-placeholder">Enter bond details to calculate yield to maturity (YTM), current yield, duration, convexity, and total return analysis.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="chart-section" id="chartSection" style="display:none">
      <h2>Price vs. Yield Curve</h2>
      <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px;margin-bottom:16px">Shows how this bond's price changes as market yields move. The dot marks the current price/yield position.</p>
      <div class="chart-wrap">
        <div class="chart-canvas-wrap">
          <canvas id="priceYieldCanvas"></canvas>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cashflow-section" id="cashflowSection" style="display:none">
      <h2>Cash Flow Schedule</h2>
      <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px;margin-bottom:16px">Breakdown of coupon payments by period with running totals showing cumulative income over the life of the bond.</p>
      <div class="table-wrap" style="max-height:400px;overflow-y:auto">
        <table id="cashflowTable">
          <thead style="position:sticky;top:0;z-index:1;background:#0c1428">
            <tr>
              <th>Period</th>
              <th class="num">Coupon Payment</th>
              <th class="num">Running Total</th>
              <th class="num">PV of Cash Flow</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody id="cashflowTbody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="comparison-section">
      <h2>Bond Comparison — Side by Side</h2>
      <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px;margin-bottom:16px">Enter two bonds to compare their yields, duration, and risk profiles.</p>
      <div class="comp-container">
        <div class="comp-bond">
          <h3>Bond A</h3>
          <div class="input-row">
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Face Value ($)</label>
              <input type="number" id="compA_face" value="1000" step="100" min="0">
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Price ($)</label>
              <input type="number" id="compA_price" placeholder="e.g. 950" step="0.01" min="0">
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-row-3">
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Coupon (%)</label>
              <input type="number" id="compA_coupon" placeholder="5.0" step="0.01" min="0">
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Years</label>
              <input type="number" id="compA_years" placeholder="10" step="0.5" min="0.5">
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Frequency</label>
              <select id="compA_freq">
                <option value="2">Semi</option>
                <option value="1">Annual</option>
                <option value="4">Quarterly</option>
              </select>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="comp-bond">
          <h3>Bond B</h3>
          <div class="input-row">
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Face Value ($)</label>
              <input type="number" id="compB_face" value="1000" step="100" min="0">
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Price ($)</label>
              <input type="number" id="compB_price" placeholder="e.g. 1050" step="0.01" min="0">
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-row-3">
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Coupon (%)</label>
              <input type="number" id="compB_coupon" placeholder="4.0" step="0.01" min="0">
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Years</label>
              <input type="number" id="compB_years" placeholder="20" step="0.5" min="0.5">
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Frequency</label>
              <select id="compB_freq">
                <option value="2">Semi</option>
                <option value="1">Annual</option>
                <option value="4">Quarterly</option>
              </select>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <button class="calc-btn" id="compBtn" style="margin-top:16px">Compare Bonds</button>
      <div id="compResults"></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Bond Pricing: Given YTM → Fair Price -->
    <div class="pricing-section">
      <h2>Bond Pricing: Calculate Fair Price from YTM</h2>
      <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px;margin-bottom:16px">Given a target yield to maturity, calculate the fair price you should pay for a bond.</p>
      <div class="pricing-grid">
        <div class="calc-inputs">
          <div class="input-row">
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Face Value ($)</label>
              <input type="number" id="pFaceValue" value="1000" step="100" min="0">
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Coupon Rate (%)</label>
              <input type="number" id="pCouponRate" placeholder="e.g. 5.0" step="0.01" min="0">
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-row">
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Target YTM (%)</label>
              <input type="number" id="pTargetYtm" placeholder="e.g. 6.0" step="0.01" min="0">
              <div class="input-hint">Your required yield to maturity</div>
            </div>
            <div class="input-group">
              <label>Years to Maturity</label>
              <input type="number" id="pYears" placeholder="e.g. 10" step="0.5" min="0.5">
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="input-group">
            <label>Payment Frequency</label>
            <select id="pFreq">
              <option value="2">Semi-Annual</option>
              <option value="1">Annual</option>
              <option value="4">Quarterly</option>
            </select>
          </div>
          <button class="calc-btn" id="priceBtn">Calculate Fair Price</button>
        </div>
        <div class="calc-results" id="priceResults">
          <div class="result-placeholder">Enter a target YTM and bond details to calculate the fair price you should pay.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ratings-section">
      <h2>Bond Credit Ratings — Reference Table</h2>
      <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:14px;margin-bottom:16px">Credit ratings assess default risk and directly impact the yield investors demand. Higher risk = higher yield.</p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>S&amp;P / Fitch</th>
              <th>Moody's</th>
              <th>Grade</th>
              <th>Description</th>
              <th class="num">Typical Spread (bps)</th>
              <th class="num">Approx. Yield</th>
              <th>Default Risk</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody id="ratingsTbody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="findings">
      <h2>Bond Yield Explained: Key Insights</h2>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>YTM Is the True Measure of Bond Return</h3>
        <p>Current yield only tells you about income — it ignores capital gains or losses at maturity. A bond bought at $900 with a 5% coupon has a current yield of 5.56%, but the $100 gain at maturity significantly boosts the true return. Yield to maturity captures both coupon income and the price difference, making it the gold standard for bond comparison. Always use YTM when deciding between bonds with different prices, coupons, and maturities.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>Duration Quantifies Your Interest Rate Risk</h3>
        <p>Modified duration tells you exactly how much your bond's price will move for a 1% change in yields. A bond with modified duration of 8 will drop roughly 8% if rates rise 1%. In a rising rate environment, shorter-duration bonds lose less value. In a falling rate environment, longer-duration bonds gain more. Duration is the single most important risk metric for bond portfolios — more useful than maturity alone because it accounts for the timing and size of all cash flows.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>Premium vs. Discount Bonds Signal Market Expectations</h3>
        <p>When a bond trades above par (premium), the market is saying its coupon is higher than current yields demand — you're paying extra for above-market income. When it trades below par (discount), the coupon is below market rates. Neither is inherently better: premium bonds provide more current income but lose value at maturity, while discount bonds provide less income but gain value. The YTM equalizes these tradeoffs, which is why two bonds with different prices and coupons can have identical YTMs.</p>
